Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which supports the euro by setting constraints determining the size of budget deficits for members of the Union, is in danger.
Germany, a heavy weight in the Union, has not succeeded in meeting its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Moreover, it used its political weight to cover the prewarning of its deficit, set up by the European Commission according to the terms of the Stability Pact.
Today it's France that's playing the bad boy.
The number two of the Union, not very enthusiastic, has come unofficially to declare a year after small Ireland received an official warning about its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, that it cannot meet its commitment to reduce the budget deficit, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the Stability Pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems very affected by the discussions aimed at eliminating it, as well as those aimed at amending it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly designed and its implementation is flawed.
The limit of the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and does not take into account the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Acknowledging this fact, the architects of the pact have worsened the situation by adopting two "poorly conceived" solutions.
They introduced a safeguard clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of a major recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is virtually impossible in practice.
Concerned that serious recessions could undermine the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit equated to zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a budget forecast for the two years ahead demonstrating how budget equilibrium will be achieved over time.
The German commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was growing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from meeting its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a fiscal policy of budgetary contraction.
The Commission, seeking to project itself as the protector of the pact, wanted to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by realpolitik figures, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany since everyone recognized they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was issued.
France's situation is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, particularly regarding tax relief.
In a country where tax burdens are high, it is not just a matter of political acumen, but also of economic wisdom, especially when budget expenditures are also reduced.
However, in France, everyone also benefits from certain privileges financed by the state, and thus budget cuts are definitively poorly perceived.
Thus, France cannot meet its targets, and the Commission expressed its frustration.
But France has mastered the art of defying the Union's rules.
Inevitably, political maneuvering will follow.
Economists and cynics are not surprised.
The goal of the pact, to establish fiscal discipline among countries sharing the same currency, is entirely reasonable.
However, losing control of their national monetary policy, members of the Union no longer benefit from any single macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to reconcile.
The Stability Pact is too simplistic and technocratic: the 3% target set by Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look far.
The monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize prices in the long term while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
In the last ten years, monetary policy achieved a real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it simply requires delegating this policy to a competent group, the Central Bank, by granting it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any misstep will have to be corrected in the future, it is up to him to exercise common sense.
This has turned out to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Of course, some fear losing democracy in the process.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy fulfills two very different objectives.
The first is structural and redistributive and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure in terms of expenditures and revenues.
Decisions concerning these issues cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments and be subject to parliamentary approval and management.
The second is macroeconomic: it concerns defining the budgetary equilibrium to manage fluctuations in the economic cycle.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain full control of its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, its decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee whose long-term objective is to stabilize (or reduce, for some countries) public debt.
To ensure its success, the status and mandates of such a Committee must be agreed upon within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary regulation, without any political decision-making, but simply by relying on common sense.
